To create this infographic, I used Canva as my main design tool. It allowed me to build a clean and simple layout without much difficulty. 
I went for a minimal style using soft blue tones and a white background so that the content looks neat and easy to read. The overall aim was to keep it visually
appealing while still being clear and student-friendly. The infographic is divided into five sections, each focusing on an important aspect of digital literacy. 
It starts with a basic explanation of what digital literacy means, followed by a section on useful platforms like GitHub and LinkedIn that can help students grow
academically and professionally. The next parts highlight safe internet practices and the importance of maintaining a good online presence. In the end, I included 
a short guide on email etiquette, since it is an important skill for communicating in college and beyond. One part I found particularly interesting was balancing
visuals and text. Choosing the right icons for ideas like public Wi-Fi safety or professional communication wasn’t as straightforward as it seemed. It made me thin
about how to represent concepts in a simple visual way. Over time, I realized that a good icon can explain an idea faster than a long sentence, which made the design
more engaging and easier to understand.
